\paragraph{Context}
The standard initial value problem is an autonomous ODE (406a) on $[x_0, x]$ with given initial value at $x_0$, using positive stepsize $h$. The method is a consistent linear multistep method with coefficients $\alpha_i$ and $\beta_i$.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $y$: exact solution to the differential equation (406a)
    \item $x$: point in the interval $[x_0, x]$ where the solution is approximated
    \item $x_0$: initial point where initial value information is given
    \item $h$: positive stepsize
    \item $k$: number of steps in the linear multistep method (implied by the method coefficients)
    \item $\alpha_i$, $\beta_i$: coefficients of the linear multistep method, with $i$ from $0$ to $k$
\end{itemize}

Referenced equations:
\begin{equation}
    y'(x) = f(y(x)) \quad \text{(autonomous ODE)}, \quad \text{with } f \text{ Lipschitz continuous}
    \tag{406a}
\end{equation}
